Alt: a bottle of food52 sits on a table next to a cutting board

Method
​Prepare the Croutons: Cube any leftover baguette and toast until crisp. Crush some of the cubes into crumbs and keep both the croutons and crumbs aside.
​Prepare the Base Toast: Lightly toast the diagonal baguette slices. Drizzle lightly with garlic-infused olive oil.
​Create the Filling: Mash the hot or warm potato and spaghetti squash. Season lightly with turmeric, black pepper, and cumin.
​Add Texture: Fold the crouton pieces and crumbs into the squash/potato mash.
​Assemble and Finish:
​Spoon a generous tablespoon of the filling onto the base toast slices.
​Return the assembled crostini to toast again until the filling is warmed through and the toast reaches one shade darker.
​Top the warm crostini with a small spoonful of chopped onion and tomato mixture (your quick salsa criolla).
​Add a thin slice of avocado and a small dab of mustard.
​Suggested Side Components
​To round out the meal and complement the warmth, seasoning, and richness of the crostini:
​Quick Lime-Marinated Cucumber:
​Thinly slice cucumber and toss it with lime juice, salt, and black pepper.
​Why it works: Provides a cold, acidic, and crisp contrast to the warm, starchy crostini.
​Simple Greens with Vinaigrette:
​Toss your salad greens with a simple dressing made from olive oil, maple syrup, and a squeeze of lemon or plum/pluot juice (for a tangy-sweet profile).
​Why it works: Offers a bitter element and a light, fresh texture to cut through the richness of the potato/squash.
​Chopped Walnuts:
​Serve a small bowl of roughly chopped walnuts on the side.
​Why it works: Provides a simple, crunchy texture and nutty flavor, echoing the contrasting textures often found in Peruvian plates.
